issue.title: Compiled model performance trends

type.name: Feature
type.description: A request, idea, or new functionality

repository.name: efcore
repository.description: EF Core is a modern object-database mapper for .NET. It supports LINQ queries, change tracking, updates, and schema migrations.

issue.body: In investigating the compiled model changes in EF9, I noticed that things were taking quite a lot longer than expected, so I did some analysis. The model here is the one used in the samples: https://github.com/dotnet/EntityFramework.Docs/tree/main/samples/core/Miscellaneous/CompiledModels The first issue is that, for this sample model with 449 entity types, 6390 properties, and 720 relationships, the startup time is now **worse** when using a compiled model. | EF version | Normal (s) | Compiled model (s) | |------------|------------|--------------------| | EF Core 6 | 3.71 | 0.93 | | EF Core 7 | 4.07 | 1.04 | | EF Core 8 | 4.52 | 3.37 | | EF Core 9 | 4.48 | 5.24 | By startup time, I mean wall clock time to run the following: ```C# using (var context = new BlogsContext()) { entityCount = context.Model.GetEntityTypes().Count(); } ``` My suspicion that a lot of this is assembly loading and/or JIT, based on the increase in DLL size across releases: | EF version | Normal (MB) | Compiled model (MB) | |------------|------------|--------------------| | EF Core 6 | 0.9 | 2 | | EF Core 7 | 0.9 | 2 | | EF Core 8 | 0.9 | 8 | | EF Core 9 | 0.9 | 20 | Related to all this is that the time to run `dotnet ef dbcontext optimize` on this same model has increased very dramatically in EF9. | EF version | Time to run `dbcontext optimize` (s) |------------|------------| | EF Core 6 | 11 | | EF Core 7 | 11 | | EF Core 8 | 40 | | EF Core 9 | 107 |

issue.title: Add UnsafeAccessor support for generic types

repository.name: efcore
repository.description: EF Core is a modern object-database mapper for .NET. It supports LINQ queries, change tracking, updates, and schema migrations.

issue.body:
- Group UnsafeAccessor methods by target type
- Generate fully qualified lambda signatures
- Generate shorter UnsafeAccessor names
- Reenable test code that uses the compiled model
- Don't use Roslyn Formatter or Simplifier to make generation faster and avoid artifacts

Fixes #33773
Fixes #33470
